#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:234
msgid "Configuring the build with spec objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:236
msgid ""
"Configuring a build is typically the first step in the build process. In "
"many build systems it involves passing the right command line arguments to "
"the configure script, and in some build systems it is a matter of setting "
"the right environment variables. In this section we will use an Autotools "
"package as an example, where we just need to implement the "
"``configure_args`` helper function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:240
msgid ""
"In general, whenever you implement helper functions of a build system or "
"complement or override its build phases, you often need to make decisions "
"based on the package's configuration. Spack is unique in that it allows you "
"to write a *single* ``package.py`` for all configurations of a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:243
msgid ""
"The central object in Spack that encodes the package's configuration is the "
"**concrete spec**, which is available as ``self.spec`` in the package class. "
"This is the object you need to query to make decisions about how to "
"configure the build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:247
msgid "Querying ``self.spec``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:249
msgid ""
"**Variants**. In the previous section of the packaging guide, we've seen :"
"ref:`how to define variants <variants>`. As a packager, you are responsible "
"for implementing the logic that translates the selected variant values into "
"build instructions the build system can understand. If you want to pass a "
"flag to the configure script only if the package is built with a specific "
"variant, you can do so like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:254
msgid ""
"variant(\"foo\", default=False, description=\"Enable foo feature\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"+foo\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-foo\")\n"
"    else:\n"
"        args.append(\"--disable-foo\")\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:267
msgid ""
"For multi-valued variants, you can use the ``key=value`` syntax to test "
"whether a specific value is selected:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:269
msgid ""
"variant(\"threads\", default=\"none\", values=(\"pthreads\", \"openmp\", "
"\"none\"), multi=False, ...)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"threads=pthreads\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-threads=pthreads\")\n"
"    elif self.spec.satisfies(\"threads=openmp\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-threads=openmp\")\n"
"    elif self.spec.satisfies(\"threads=none\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--disable-threads\")\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:284
msgid ""
"Even if *multiple* values are selected, you can still use ``key=value`` to "
"test for specific values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:286
msgid ""
"variant(\"languages\", default=\"c,c++\", values=(\"c\", \"c++\", "
"\"fortran\"), multi=True, ...)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"languages=c\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-c\")\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"languages=c++\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-c++\")\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"languages=fortran\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-fortran\")\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:301
msgid ""
"Notice that many build systems provide helper functions to make the above "
"code more concise. See :ref:`the Autotools docs "
"<autotools_helper_functions>` and :ref:`the CMake docs <cmake_args>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:304
msgid ""
"Other than testing for certain variant values, you can also obtain the "
"variant value directly with ``self.spec.variants[\"variant_name\"].value``. "
"This is useful when you want to pass the variant value as a command line "
"argument to the build system. The type of this value depends on the variant "
"type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:308
msgid "For boolean variants this is :data:`True` or :data:`False`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:309
msgid "For single-valued variants this is a :class:`str` value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:310
msgid "For multi-valued variants it is a tuple of :class:`str` values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:312
msgid "An example of using this is shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:314
msgid ""
"variant(\n"
"    \"cxxstd\",\n"
"    default=\"11\",\n"
"    values=(\"11\", \"14\", \"17\", \"20\", \"23\"),\n"
"    multi=False,\n"
"    description=\"C++ standard\",\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    return [f\"--with-cxxstd={self.spec.variants['cxxstd'].value}\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:328
msgid ""
"**Versions**. Similarly, versions are often used to dynamically change the "
"build configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:331
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"@1.2:\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-new-feature\")\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:339
msgid "This adds a flag only if the package is on version 1.2 or higher."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:341
msgid ""
"**Dependencies**. You can also use the ``self.spec.satisfies`` method to "
"test whether a dependency is present or not, and whether it is built with a "
"specific variant or version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:344
msgid ""
"The ``^`` character is used to refer to packages that are required at "
"runtime as well as build dependencies. More precisely, it includes all "
"direct dependencies of ``build`` type and transitive dependencies of "
"``link`` or ``run`` type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:347
msgid ""
"if self.spec.satisfies(\"^python@3.8:\"):\n"
"    args.append(\"--min-python-version=3.8\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:352
msgid ""
"Here we test whether the package has a (possibly transitive) dependency on "
"Python version 3.8 or higher."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:354
msgid ""
"The ``%`` character is used to refer to direct dependencies only. A typical "
"use case is when you want to test the compiler used to build the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:357
msgid ""
"if self.spec.satisfies(\"%c=gcc@8:\"):\n"
"    args.append(\"--enable-profile-guided-optimization\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:362
msgid ""
"This example adds a flag when the C compiler is from GCC version 8 or "
"higher. The ``%c=gcc`` syntax technically means that ``gcc`` is the provider "
"for the ``c`` language virtual."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:367
msgid ""
"Historically, many packages have been written using ``^dep`` to refer to a "
"dependency. Modern Spack packages should consider using ``%dep`` instead, "
"which is more precise: it can only match direct dependencies, which are "
"listed in the ``depends_on`` statements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:371
msgid ""
"**Target specific configuration**. Spack always makes the special "
"``platform``, ``os`` and ``target`` variants available in the spec. These "
"variants can be used to test the target platform, operating system and CPU "
"microarchitecture the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:375
msgid ""
"The following example shows how we can add a configure option only if the "
"package is built for Apple Silicon:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:377
msgid ""
"if self.spec.satisfies(\"platform=darwin target=aarch64:\"):\n"
"    args.append(\"--enable-apple-silicon\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:382
msgid ""
"Notice that ``target=aarch64:`` is a range which matches the whole family of "
"``aarch64`` microarchitectures, including ``m1``, ``m2``, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:384
msgid ""
"You can use ranges starting at a specific microarchitecture as well, for "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:386
msgid ""
"if self.spec.satisfies(\"target=haswell:\"):\n"
"    args.append(\"--enable-haswell\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:393
msgid ""
"The ``spec`` object encodes the *target* platform, os and architecture the "
"package is being built for. This is different from the *host* platform "
"(typically accessed via ``sys.platform``) which is the platform where Spack "
"is running. When writing package recipes, you should always use the ``spec`` "
"object to query the target platform, os and architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:397
msgid ""
"To see what targets are available in your Spack installation, you can use "
"the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:402
msgid "Referring to a dependency's prefix, libraries, and headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:404
msgid ""
"Very often you need to inform the build system about the location of a "
"dependency. The most common way to do this is to pass the dependency's "
"prefix as a configure argument and let the build system detect the libraries "
"and headers from there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:407
msgid "To do this, you can obtain the **dependency's spec** by name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:409
msgid "libxml2 = self.spec[\"libxml2\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:413
msgid ""
"The ``libxml2`` variable is itself a spec object, and we can refer to its "
"properties:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:415
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    return [\n"
"        f\"--with-libxml2={self.spec['libxml2'].prefix}\",\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:422
msgid ""
"Apart from the :ref:`prefix <prefix-objects>`, you can also access other "
"attributes of the dependency, such as ``libs`` or ``headers``. See :ref:"
"`custom-attributes` for how dependencies define these attributes. These "
"attributes are typically only required if the package is unable to locate "
"the libraries and headers itself, or if you want to be more specific about "
"which libraries or headers to use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:426
msgid ""
"A more advanced example where we explicitly pass libraries and headers to "
"the configure script is shown below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:428
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    return [\n"
"        f\"--with-libxml2={self.spec['libxml2'].prefix}\",\n"
"        f\"--with-libxml2-libs={self.spec['libxml2'].libs.ld_flags}\",\n"
"        f\"--with-libxml2-include={self.spec['libxml2'].headers."
"include_flags}\",\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:437
msgid ""
"The ``libs`` attribute is a :class:`~spack.package.LibraryList` object that "
"can be used to get a list of libraries by path, but also to get the "
"appropriate linker flags. Similarly, the ``headers`` attribute is a :class:"
"`~spack.package.HeaderList`, which also has methods to get the relevant "
"include flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:442
msgid ""
"**Virtual dependencies**. You can also refer to the prefix, libraries and "
"headers of :ref:`virtual dependencies <virtual-dependencies>`. For example, "
"suppose we have a package that depends on ``blas`` and ``lapack``. We can "
"get the provider's (e.g. OpenBLAS or Intel MKL) prefixes like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:447
msgid ""
"class MyPkg(AutotoolPackage):\n"
"    depends_on(\"blas\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"lapack\")\n"
"\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        return [\n"
"            f\"--with-blas={self.spec['blas'].prefix}\",\n"
"            f\"--with-lapack={self.spec['lapack'].prefix}\",\n"
"        ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:459
msgid ""
"Many build systems struggle to locate the ``blas`` and ``lapack`` libraries "
"during configure, either because they do not know the exact names of the "
"libraries, or because the libraries are not in typical locations --- they "
"may not even know whether ``blas`` and ``lapack`` are a single or separate "
"libraries. In those cases, the build system could use some help, for which "
"we give a few examples below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:462
msgid "Space separated list of full paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:464
msgid ""
"lapack_blas = spec[\"lapack\"].libs + spec[\"blas\"].libs\n"
"args.append(f\"--with-blas-lapack-lib={lapack_blas.joined()}\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:469
msgid "Names of libraries and directories which contain them"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:471
msgid ""
"lapack_blas = spec[\"lapack\"].libs + spec[\"blas\"].libs\n"
"args.extend(\n"
"    [\n"
"        f\"-DMATH_LIBRARY_NAMES={';'.join(lapack_blas.names)}\",\n"
"        f\"-DMATH_LIBRARY_DIRS={';'.join(lapack_blas.directories)}\",\n"
"    ]\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:481
msgid "Search and link flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:483
msgid ""
"lapack_blas = spec[\"lapack\"].libs + spec[\"blas\"].libs\n"
"args.append(f\"-DMATH_LIBS={lapack_blas.ld_flags}\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:492
msgid "Before and after build phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:494
msgid ""
"Typically the default implementation of the build system's phases is "
"sufficient for most packages. However, in some cases you may need to "
"complement the default implementation with some custom instructions. For "
"example, some packages do not install all the files they should, and you "
"want to fix this by simply copying the missing files after the normal "
"install phase is done. Instead of overriding the entire phase, you can use "
"``@run_before`` and ``@run_after`` to run custom code before or after a "
"specific phase:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:499
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(CMakePackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    variant(\"extras\", default=False, description=\"Install extra files\")\n"
"\n"
"    @run_before(\"cmake\")\n"
"    def run_before_cmake_is_invoked(self) -> None:\n"
"        with open(\"custom_file.txt\", \"w\") as f:\n"
"            f.write(\"This file is created before cmake is invoked.\")\n"
"\n"
"    @run_after(\"install\", when=\"+extras\")\n"
"    def custom_post_install_phase(self) -> None:\n"
"        # install missing files not covered by the build system\n"
"        install_tree(\"extras\", self.prefix.share.extras)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:516
msgid ""
"Then ``when=\"+extras\"`` will ensure that the custom post-install phase is "
"only run conditionally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:518
msgid ""
"The function body should contain the actual instructions you want to run "
"before or after the build phase, which can involve :ref:`running executables "
"<running_build_executables>` and creating or copying files to the ``prefix`` "
"directory using convenience functions from :ref:`Spack's Python Package API "
"<python-package-api>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:523
msgid "Overriding a build phase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:525
msgid ""
"If a build phase does not do what you need, and you cannot achieve your goal "
"either by implementing the helper methods of the build system, or by using "
"the ``@run_before`` or ``@run_after`` decorators (see :ref:"
"`before_after_build_phases`), you can override the entire build phase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:527
msgid ""
"The most common scenario is when a package simply does not have a well-"
"defined build system. For example, the installation procedure may just be "
"copying files or running a shell script. In that case, you can use the "
"generic ``Package`` class, which defines only a single ``install()`` phase, "
"to be overridden by the package author:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:531
msgid ""
"from spack.package import *\n"
"from spack_repo.builtin.build_systems.generic import Package\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPkg(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    # Override the install phase\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix) -> None:\n"
"        install_tree(\"my_files\", prefix.bin)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:543
msgid ""
"Whichever build system is used, **every build phase function has the same "
"set of arguments**. The arguments are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:546
msgid "``self``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:547
msgid ""
"This is the package object, which extends ``CMakePackage``. For API docs on "
"Package objects, see :py:class:`Package <spack.package.PackageBase>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:550
msgid "``spec``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:551
msgid ""
"This is the concrete spec object created by Spack from an abstract spec "
"supplied by the user. It describes what should be installed. It will be of "
"type :py:class:`Spec <spack.package.Spec>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:555
msgid "``prefix``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:556
msgid ""
"This is where your package should install its files. It acts like a string, "
"but it's actually its :ref:`own special type <prefix-objects>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:559
msgid ""
"The function body should contain the actual build instructions, which "
"typically involves:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:561
msgid ""
"Invoking the build system's commands such as ``make``, ``ninja``, "
"``python``, et cetera. See :ref:`running_build_executables` for how to do "
"this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:563
msgid ""
"Copying files to the ``prefix`` directory, which is where Spack expects the "
"package to be installed. This can be done using Spack's built-in functions "
"like ``install_tree()`` or ``install()``. See the :ref:`Spack's Python "
"Package API <python-package-api>` for all convenience functions that can be "
"used in the package class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:567
msgid ""
"The arguments ``spec`` and ``prefix`` are passed only for convenience, as "
"they always correspond to ``self.spec`` and ``self.spec.prefix`` "
"respectively, as we have already seen in :ref:`the previous section <spec-"
"objects>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:571
msgid ""
"When working with :ref:`multiple build systems <multiple_build_systems>` in "
"a single package, the arguments for build phase functions are slightly "
"different."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:576
msgid "Running build executables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:578
msgid ""
"When you :ref:`override a build phase <overriding-phases>`, or when you "
"write a :ref:`build phase hook <before_after_build_phases>`, you typically "
"need to invoke executables like ``make``, ``cmake``, or ``python`` to kick "
"off the build process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:580
msgid ""
"Spack makes some of these executables available as global functions, making "
"it easy to run them in your package class:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:582
msgid ""
"from spack.package import *\n"
"from spack_repo.builtin.build_systems.generic import Package\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPkg(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"make\", type=\"build\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"python\", type=\"build\")\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix) -> None:\n"
"        python(\"generate-makefile.py\", \"--output=Makefile\")\n"
"        make()\n"
"        make(\"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:598
msgid ""
"The ``python()`` and ``make()`` functions in this example invoke the "
"``python3`` and ``make`` executables, respectively. Naturally, you may "
"wonder where these variables come from, since they are not imported from "
"anywhere --- your editor may even underline them in red because they are not "
"defined in the package module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:601
msgid ""
"The answer lies in the ``python`` and ``make`` dependencies, which implement "
"the :meth:`~spack.package.PackageBase.setup_dependent_package` method in "
"their package classes. This sets up Python variables that can be used in the "
"package class of dependents."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:604
msgid ""
"There is a good reason that it's the *dependency* that sets up these "
"variables, rather than the package itself. For example, the ``make`` package "
"ensures sensible default arguments for the ``make`` executable, such as the "
"``-j`` flag to enable parallel builds. This means that you do not have to "
"worry about these technical details in your package class; you can just use "
"``make(\"my_target\")`` and Spack will take care of the rest. See the "
"section about :ref:`parallel builds <attribute_parallel>` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:609
msgid ""
"Not all dependencies set up such variables for dependent packages, in which "
"case you have two further options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:611
msgid ""
"Use the ``command`` attribute of the dependency. This is a good option, "
"since it refers to an executable provided by a specific dependency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:614
msgid ""
"def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix) -> None:\n"
"    cython = self.spec[\"py-cython\"].command\n"
"    cython(\"setup.py\", \"build_ext\", \"--inplace\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:620
msgid ""
"Use the ``which`` function (from the ``spack.package`` module). Do note that "
"this function relies on the order of the ``PATH`` environment variable, "
"which may be less reliable than the first option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:623
msgid ""
"def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix) -> None:\n"
"    cython = which(\"cython\", required=True)\n"
"    cython(\"setup.py\", \"build_ext\", \"--inplace\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:629
msgid ""
"All executables in Spack are instances of :class:`~spack.package."
"Executable`, see its API docs for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:635
msgid "Package-level parallelism"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:637
msgid ""
"Many build tools support parallel builds, including ``make`` and ``ninja``, "
"as well as certain Python build tools."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:639
msgid ""
"As mentioned in :ref:`the previous section <running_build_executables>`, the "
"``gmake`` and ``ninja`` packages make their executables available as global "
"functions, which you can use in your package class. They automatically add "
"the ``-j <njobs>`` when invoked, where ``<njobs>`` is a sensible default for "
"the number of jobs to run in parallel. This exact number :ref:`is determined "
"<build-jobs>` depends on various factors, such as the ``spack install`` "
"command line arguments, configuration options and available CPUs on the "
"system. As a packager, you rarely need to pass the ``-j`` flag when calling "
"``make()`` or ``ninja()``; it is better to rely on the defaults."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:644
msgid ""
"In certain cases however, you may need to override the default number of "
"jobs for a specific package. If a package does not build properly in "
"parallel, you can simply define ``parallel = False`` in your package class. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:648
msgid ""
"class ExamplePackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"Example package that does not build in parallel.\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"    parallel = False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:656
msgid ""
"This ensures that any ``make`` or ``ninja`` invocation will *not* set the ``-"
"j <njobs>`` option, and the build will run sequentially."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:658
msgid "You can also disable parallel builds only for specific make invocation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:660
msgid ""
"class Libelf(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix) -> None:\n"
"        make(\"install\", parallel=False)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:669
msgid ""
"In this case, the ``build`` phase will still execute in parallel, but the "
"``install`` phase will run sequentially."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:671
msgid ""
"For packages whose build systems do not run ``make`` or ``ninja``, but have "
"other executables or scripts that support parallel builds, you can control "
"parallelism using the ``make_jobs`` global. This global variable is an "
"integer that specifies the number of jobs to run in parallel during the "
"build process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:674
msgid ""
"class Xios(Package):\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix) -> None:\n"
"        make_xios = Executable(\"./make_xios\")\n"
"        make_xios(\n"
"            \"--with-feature\",\n"
"            f\"--jobs={make_jobs}\",\n"
"        )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:688
msgid "Spack's Python Package API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:690
msgid ""
"Whenever you implement :ref:`overriding phases <overriding-phases>` or :ref:"
"`before and after build phases <before_after_build_phases>`, you typically "
"need to modify files, work with paths and run executables. Spack provides a "
"number of convenience functions and classes of its own to make your life "
"even easier, complementing the Python standard library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:693
msgid ""
"All of the functionality in this section is made available by importing the :"
"mod:`spack.package` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:695
msgid "from spack.package import *"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:699
msgid ""
"This is already part of the boilerplate for packages created with ``spack "
"create``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:704
msgid "File filtering functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:706
msgid ""
":py:func:`filter_file(regex, repl, *filenames, **kwargs) <spack.package."
"filter_file>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:707
msgid ""
"Works like ``sed`` but with Python regular expression syntax. Takes a "
"regular expression, a replacement, and a set of files. ``repl`` can be a raw "
"string or a callable function. If it is a raw string, it can contain "
"``\\1``, ``\\2``, etc. to refer to capture groups in the regular expression. "
"If it is a callable, it is passed the Python ``MatchObject`` and should "
"return a suitable replacement string for the particular match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:713
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:715
msgid "Filtering a Makefile to force it to use Spack's compiler wrappers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:717
msgid ""
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*CC\\s*=.*\", \"CC = \" + spack_cc, \"Makefile\")\n"
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*CXX\\s*=.*\", \"CXX = \" + spack_cxx, \"Makefile\")\n"
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*F77\\s*=.*\", \"F77 = \" + spack_f77, \"Makefile\")\n"
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*FC\\s*=.*\", \"FC = \" + spack_fc, \"Makefile\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:724
msgid ""
"Replacing ``#!/usr/bin/perl`` with ``#!/usr/bin/env perl`` in ``bib2xhtml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:726
msgid ""
"filter_file(r\"#!/usr/bin/perl\", \"#!/usr/bin/env perl\", prefix.bin."
"bib2xhtml)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:730
msgid ""
"Switching the compilers used by ``mpich``'s MPI wrapper scripts from ``cc``, "
"etc. to the compilers used by the Spack build:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:732
msgid ""
"filter_file(\"CC='cc'\", \"CC='%s'\" % self.compiler.cc, prefix.bin.mpicc)\n"
"filter_file(\"CXX='c++'\", \"CXX='%s'\" % self.compiler.cxx, prefix.bin."
"mpicxx)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:737
msgid ""
":py:func:`change_sed_delimiter(old_delim, new_delim, *filenames) <spack."
"package.change_sed_delimiter>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:738
msgid ""
"Some packages, like TAU, have a build system that can't install into "
"directories with, e.g. \"@\" in the name, because they use hard-coded "
"``sed`` commands in their build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:740
msgid ""
"``change_sed_delimiter`` finds all ``sed`` search/replace commands and "
"changes the delimiter. E.g., if the file contains commands that look like "
"``s///``, you can use this to change them to ``s@@@``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:743
msgid "Example of changing ``s///`` to ``s@@@`` in TAU:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:745
msgid ""
"change_sed_delimiter(\"@\", \";\", \"configure\")\n"
"change_sed_delimiter(\"@\", \";\", \"utils/FixMakefile\")\n"
"change_sed_delimiter(\"@\", \";\", \"utils/FixMakefile.sed.default\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:752
msgid "File functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:754
msgid ":py:func:`ancestor(dir, n=1) <spack.package.ancestor>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:755
msgid "Get the n\\ :sup:`th` ancestor of the directory ``dir``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:757
msgid ":py:func:`can_access(path) <spack.package.can_access>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:758
msgid ""
"True if we can read and write to the file at ``path``. Same as native Python "
"``os.access(file_name, os.R_OK|os.W_OK)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:761
msgid ":py:func:`install(src, dest) <spack.package.install>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:762
msgid ""
"Install a file to a particular location. For example, install a header into "
"the ``include`` directory under the install ``prefix``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:765
msgid "install(\"my-header.h\", prefix.include)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:769
msgid ":py:func:`join_path(*paths) <spack.package.join_path>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:770
msgid ""
"An alias for ``os.path.join``. This joins paths using the OS path separator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:773
msgid ":py:func:`mkdirp(*paths) <spack.package.mkdirp>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:774
msgid ""
"Create each of the directories in ``paths``, creating any parent directories "
"if they do not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:776
msgid ":py:func:`working_dir(dirname, kwargs) <spack.package.working_dir>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:777
msgid ""
"This is a Python `Context Manager <https://docs.python.org/2/library/"
"contextlib.html>`_ that makes it easier to work with subdirectories in "
"builds. You use this with the Python ``with`` statement to change into a "
"working directory, and when the with block is done, you change back to the "
"original directory. Think of it as a safe ``pushd`` / ``popd`` combination, "
"where ``popd`` is guaranteed to be called at the end, even if exceptions are "
"thrown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:781
msgid "Example usage:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:783
msgid ""
"The ``libdwarf`` build first runs ``configure`` and ``make`` in a "
"subdirectory called ``libdwarf``. It then implements the installation code "
"itself. This is natural with ``working_dir``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:787
msgid ""
"with working_dir(\"libdwarf\"):\n"
"    configure(\"--prefix=\" + prefix, \"--enable-shared\")\n"
"    make()\n"
"    install(\"libdwarf.a\", prefix.lib)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:794
msgid ""
"Many CMake builds require that you build \"out of source\", that is, in a "
"subdirectory. You can handle creating and ``cd``'ing to the subdirectory "
"like the LLVM package does:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:797
msgid ""
"with working_dir(\"spack-build\", create=True):\n"
"    cmake(\n"
"        \"..\",\n"
"        \"-DLLVM_REQUIRES_RTTI=1\",\n"
"        \"-DPYTHON_EXECUTABLE=/usr/bin/python\",\n"
"        \"-DPYTHON_INCLUDE_DIR=/usr/include/python2.6\",\n"
"        \"-DPYTHON_LIBRARY=/usr/lib64/libpython2.6.so\",\n"
"        *std_cmake_args\n"
"    )\n"
"    make()\n"
"    make(\"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:811
msgid ""
"The ``create=True`` keyword argument causes the command to create the "
"directory if it does not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:813
msgid ":py:func:`touch(path) <spack.package.touch>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:814
msgid "Create an empty file at ``path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:820
msgid "Multimethods and the ``@when`` decorator"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:822
msgid ""
"The ``@when`` annotation lets packages declare multiple versions of a method "
"that will be called depending on the package's spec. This can be useful to "
"handle cases where configure options are entirely different depending on the "
"version of the package, or when the package is built for different platforms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:825
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"@:1\")\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        return [\"--old-flag\"]\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"@2:\")\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        return [\"--new-flag\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:838
msgid ""
"You can write multiple ``@when`` specs that satisfy the package's spec, for "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:840
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\"mpi\")\n"
"\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # the default, called when no @when specs match\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^mpi@3:\")\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # this will be called when mpi is version 3 or higher\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^mpi@2:\")\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # this will be called when mpi is version 2 or higher\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^mpi@1:\")\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # this will be called when mpi is version 1 or higher\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:865
msgid ""
"In situations like this, the first matching spec, in declaration order, will "
"be called. If no ``@when`` spec matches, the default method (the one without "
"the ``@when`` decorator) will be called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:870
msgid ""
"The default method (without the ``@when`` decorator) should come first in "
"the declaration order. If not, it will erase all ``@when`` methods that "
"precede it in the class. This is a limitation of decorators in Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:878
msgid "Prefix objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:880
msgid ""
"You can find the installation directory of package in Spack by using the "
"``self.prefix`` attribute of the package object. In :ref:`overriding-"
"phases`, we saw that the ``install()`` method has a ``prefix`` argument, "
"which is the same as ``self.prefix``. This variable behaves like a string, "
"but it is actually an instance of the :py:class:`Prefix <spack.package."
"Prefix>` class, which provides some additional functionality to make it "
"easier to work with file paths in Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:884
msgid ""
"In particular, you can use the ``.`` operator to join paths together, "
"creating nested directory structures:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:887
msgid "Prefix Attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:887
msgid "Location"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:889
msgid "``prefix.bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:889
msgid "``$prefix/bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:890
msgid "``prefix.lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:890
msgid "``$prefix/lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:891
msgid "``prefix.share.man``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:891
msgid "``$prefix/share/man``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:892
msgid "``prefix.foo.bar.baz``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:892
msgid "``$prefix/foo/bar/baz``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:895
msgid ""
"Of course, this only works if your file or directory is a valid Python "
"variable name. If your file or directory contains dashes or dots, use "
"``join`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:898
msgid "prefix.lib.join(\"libz.a\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:906
msgid "The build environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:908
msgid ""
"In Spack the term **build environment** is used somewhat interchangeably to "
"refer to two things:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:910
msgid "The set of *environment variables* during the build process"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:911
msgid "The *process* in which the build is executed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:913
msgid ""
"Spack creates a separate process for each package build, and every build has "
"its own environment variables. Changes in the build environment do not "
"affect the Spack process itself, and they are not visible to other builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:916
msgid "Spack manages the build environment in the following ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:918
msgid ""
"It cleans the environment variables that may interfere with the build "
"process (e.g. ``CFLAGS``, ``LD_LIBRARY_PATH``, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:919
msgid ""
"It sets a couple of variables for its own use, prefixed with ``SPACK_*``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:920
msgid ""
"It sets a number of standard environment variables like ``PATH`` to make "
"dependencies available during the build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:921
msgid ""
"It sets custom, package specific environment variables defined in the "
"package class of dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:923
msgid ""
"For this guide, all that matters is to have a rough understanding of which "
"environments you are supposed to set in your package, and which ones are set "
"by Spack automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:925
msgid ""
"The following variables are considered \"standard\" and are managed by Spack:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:928
msgid "``PATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:928
msgid "Set to point to ``/bin`` directories of dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:929
msgid "``CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:929
msgid "Path to dependency prefixes for CMake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:930
msgid "``PKG_CONFIG_PATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:930
msgid "Path to any pkgconfig directories for dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:933
msgid ""
"Other typical environment variables such as ``CC``, ``CXX`` and ``FC`` are "
"set by the ``compiler-wrapper`` package. In your package, all you need to "
"specify is language dependencies:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:936
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(Package):\n"
"    depends_on(\"c\", type=\"build\")  # ensures CC is set\n"
"    depends_on(\"cxx\", type=\"build\")  # ensures CXX is set\n"
"    depends_on(\"fortran\", type=\"build\")  # ensures FC is set"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:943
msgid ""
"The ``compiler-wrapper`` package is an \"injected\" dependency by the "
"compiler package (which provides the ``c``, ``cxx``, and ``fortran`` "
"virtuals). It takes care of setting the ``CC``, ``CXX``, and ``FC`` "
"environment variables to the appropriate compiler executables, so you do not "
"need to set them manually in your package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:946
msgid ""
"For other compiler related environment variables such as ``CFLAGS`` and "
"``CXXFLAGS``, see :ref:`compiler flags <compiler_flags>`. This requires a "
"section of its own, because there are multiple ways to deal with compiler "
"flags, and they can come from different sources."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:952
msgid "Package specific environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:954
msgid ""
"Spack provides a few methods to help package authors set environment "
"variables programmatically. In total there are four such methods, "
"distinguishing between the build and run environments, and between the "
"package itself and its dependents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:957
msgid ""
":meth:`setup_build_environment(env, spec) <spack.package.BaseBuilder."
"setup_build_environment>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:958
msgid ""
":meth:`setup_dependent_build_environment(env, dependent_spec) <spack.package."
"BaseBuilder.setup_dependent_build_environment>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:959
msgid ""
":meth:`setup_run_environment(env) <spack.package.PackageBase."
"setup_run_environment>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:960
msgid ""
":meth:`setup_dependent_run_environment(env, dependent_spec) <spack.package."
"PackageBase.setup_dependent_run_environment>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:962
msgid ""
"All these methods take an ``env`` argument, which is an instance of the :"
"class:`EnvironmentModifications <spack.package.EnvironmentModifications>` "
"class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:964
msgid ""
"The ``setup_build_environment`` method is for certain build systems (e.g. "
"``PythonPackage``) roughly equivalent to the ``configure_args`` or "
"``cmake_args`` methods. It allows you to set environment variables that are "
"needed during the build of the package itself, and can be used to inform the "
"build system about the package's configuration and where to find "
"dependencies:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:967
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(PythonPackage):\n"
"    def setup_build_environment(self, env: EnvironmentModifications) -> "
"None:\n"
"        env.set(\"ENABLE_MY_FEATURE\", self.spec."
"satisfies(\"+my_feature\"))\n"
"        env.set(\"HDF5_DIR\", self.spec[\"hdf5\"].prefix)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:974
msgid ""
"The ``setup_dependent_build_environment`` method is similar, but it is "
"called for packages that depend on this package. This is often helpful to "
"avoid repetitive configuration in dependent packages. As an example, a "
"package like ``qt`` may want ``QTDIR`` to be set in the build environment of "
"packages that depend on it. This can be done by overriding the "
"``setup_dependent_build_environment`` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:979
msgid ""
"class Qt(Package):\n"
"    def setup_dependent_build_environment(\n"
"        self, env: EnvironmentModifications, dependent_spec: Spec\n"
"    ) -> None:\n"
"        env.set(\"QTDIR\", self.prefix)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:987
msgid ""
"The ``setup_run_environment`` and ``setup_dependent_run_environment`` are "
"the counterparts for the run environment, primarily used in commands like "
"``spack load`` and ``spack env activate``. Do note however that these "
"runtime environment variables are *also* relevant during the build process, "
"since Spack effectively creates the runtime environment of build "
"dependencies as part of the build process. For example, if a package ``my-"
"pkg`` depends on ``autoconf`` as a build dependency, and ``autoconf`` needs "
"``perl`` at runtime, then ``perl``'s runtime environment will be set up "
"during the build of ``my-pkg``. The following diagram will give you an idea "
"when each of these methods is called in a build context:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:995
msgid ""
"Notice that ``setup_dependent_run_environment`` is called once for each "
"dependent package, whereas ``setup_run_environment`` is called only once for "
"the package itself. This means that the former should only be used if the "
"environment variables depend on the dependent package, whereas the latter "
"should be used if the environment variables depend only on the package "
"itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1001
msgid "Setting package module variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1003
msgid ""
"Apart from modifying environment variables of the dependent package, you can "
"also define Python variables to be used by the dependent. This is done by "
"implementing :meth:`setup_dependent_package <spack.package.PackageBase."
"setup_dependent_package>`. An example of this can be found in the ``Python`` "
"package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1007
msgid ""
"    def setup_dependent_package(self, module, dependent_spec):\n"
"        \"\"\"Called before python modules' install() methods.\"\"\"\n"
"        module.python = self.command\n"
"        module.python_include = join_path(dependent_spec.prefix, self."
"include)\n"
"        module.python_platlib = join_path(dependent_spec.prefix, self."
"platlib)\n"
"        module.python_purelib = join_path(dependent_spec.prefix, self."
"purelib)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1011
msgid "This allows Python packages to directly use these variables:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1013
msgid ""
"def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    install(\"script.py\", python_platlib)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1021
msgid ""
"We recommend using ``setup_dependent_package`` sparingly, as it is not "
"always clear where global variables are coming from when editing a ``package."
"py`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1027
msgid "Compiler flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1029
msgid ""
"Setting compiler flags is a common task, but there are some subtleties that "
"you should be aware of. Compiler flags can be set in three different places:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1032
msgid ""
"The end user, who can set flags directly from the command line with ``spack "
"install pkg cflags=-O3`` variants or :doc:`compiler configuration "
"<packages_yaml>`. In either case, these flags become part of the :ref:"
"`concrete spec <spec-objects>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1034
msgid "The package author, who defines flags in the package class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1035
msgid ""
"The build system itself, which typically has defaults like ``CFLAGS ?= -O2 -"
"g`` or presets like ``CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1037
msgid ""
"The main challenge for packagers is to ensure that these flags are combined "
"and applied correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1041
msgid ""
"A common pitfall when dealing with compiler flags in ``MakefilePackage`` and "
"``AutotoolsPackage`` is that the user and package author specified flags "
"override the build system defaults. This can inadvertently lead to "
"unoptimized builds. For example, suppose a user requests ``spack install pkg "
"cflags=-Wno-unused`` and the build system defaults to ``CFLAGS=-O2 -g``. If "
"the package takes the user request literally and sets ``CFLAGS=-Wextra`` as "
"an environment variable, then the user-specified flags may *override* the "
"build system defaults, and the build would not be optimized: the ``-O2`` "
"flag would be lost. Whether environment variables like ``CFLAGS`` lead to "
"this problem depends on the build system, and may differ from package to "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1047
msgid ""
"Because of this pitfall, Spack tries to work around the build system and "
"defaults to **injecting compiler flags** through the compiler wrappers. This "
"means that the build system is unaware of the extra compiler flags added by "
"Spack. It also means that package authors typically do not need to deal with "
"user-specified compiler flags when writing their package classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1051
msgid ""
"However, there are two cases in which you may need to deal with compiler "
"flags in your package class explicitly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1053
msgid ""
"You need to pass default compiler flags to make a build work. This is "
"typical for packages that do not have a configure phase, and requires *you* "
"to set the appropriate flags per compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1055
msgid ""
"The build system *needs to be aware* of the user-specified compiler flags to "
"prevent a build failure. This is less common, but there are examples of "
"packages that fail to build when ``-O3`` is used for a specific source file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1058
msgid ""
"In these cases, you can implement the :meth:`flag_handler <spack.package."
"PackageBase.flag_handler>` method in your package class. This method has a "
"curious return type, but once you understand it, it is quite powerful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1061
msgid "Here is a simple example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1063
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    def flag_handler(self, name: str, flags: List[str]):\n"
"        if name in (\"cflags\", \"cxxflags\"):\n"
"            # Add optimization flags for C/C++\n"
"            flags.append(\"-O3\")\n"
"        if name == \"fflags\" and self.spec.satisfies(\"%fortran=gcc@14:"
"\"):\n"
"            # Add a specific flag for Fortran when using GCC 14 or higher\n"
"            flags.append(\"-fallow-argument-mismatch\")\n"
"        # Pass these flags to the compiler wrappers\n"
"        return (flags, None, None)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1076
msgid ""
"There are multiple things to unpack in this example, so let's go through "
"them step by step. The ``flag_handler`` method is called by Spack once for "
"each of the compiler flags supported in Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1079
msgid "The ``name`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1080
msgid ""
"The ``name`` parameter is a string that indicates which compiler flag is "
"being processed. It can be one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1083
msgid "``cppflags``: C preprocessor flags (e.g. ``-DMY_DEFINE=1``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1084
msgid "``cflags``: C compilation flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1085
msgid "``cxxflags``: C++ compilation flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1086
msgid "``fflags``: Fortran compilation flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1087
msgid "``ldflags``: Compiler flags for linking (e.g. ``-Wl,-Bstatic``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1088
msgid "``ldlibs``: Libraries to link against (e.g. ``-lfoo``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1090
msgid "The ``flags`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1091
msgid ""
"The ``flags`` parameter is a list that already contains the user-specified "
"flags, and you can modify it as needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1093
msgid "Return value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1094
msgid ""
"The return value determines *how* the flags are applied in the build "
"process. It is a triplet that contains the list of flags:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1097
msgid ""
"``(flags, None, None)``: inject the flags through the Spack **compiler "
"wrappers**. This is the default behavior, and it means that the flags are "
"applied directly to the compiler commands without the build system needing "
"to know about them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1099
msgid ""
"``(None, flags, None)``: set these flags in **environment variables** like "
"``CFLAGS``,   ``CXXFLAGS``, etc. This requires the build system to use these "
"environment variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1101
msgid ""
"``(None, None, flags)``: pass these flags **\"on the command line\"** to the "
"build system. This requires the build system to support passing flags in "
"this way. An example of a build system that supports this is "
"``CMakePackage``, and Spack will invoke ``cmake -DCMAKE_C_FLAGS=...`` and "
"similar for the other flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1105
msgid ""
"Spack also allows you to refer to common compiler flags in a more generic "
"way, using the ``self.compiler`` object. This includes flags to set the C "
"and C++ standard, as well as the compiler specific OpenMP flags, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1108
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    def flag_handler(self, name: str, flags: List[str]):\n"
"        if name == \"cflags\":\n"
"            # Set the C standard to C11\n"
"            flags.append(self.compiler.c11_flag)\n"
"        elif name == \"cxxflags\":\n"
"            # Set the C++ standard to C++17\n"
"            flags.append(self.compiler.cxx17_flag)\n"
"        return (flags, None, None)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1120
msgid ""
"If you just want to influence how the flags are passed *without setting "
"additional flags* in your package, Spack provides the following shortcut. To "
"ensure that flags are always set as *environment variables*, you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1123
msgid ""
"from spack.package import *  # for env_flags\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    flag_handler = env_flags  # Use environment variables for all flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1131
msgid ""
"To ensure that flags are always *passed to the build system*, you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1133
msgid ""
"from spack.package import *  # for build_system_flags\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    flag_handler = build_system_flags  # Pass flags to the build system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1145
msgid "Compiler wrappers and flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1147
msgid ""
"As mentioned in the :ref:`build environment <environment-variables>` "
"section, any package that depends on a language virtual (``c``, ``cxx``, or "
"``fortran``) not only gets a specific compiler package like ``gcc`` or "
"``llvm`` as a dependency, but also automatically gets the ``compiler-"
"wrapper`` package injected as a dependency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1149
msgid "The ``compiler-wrapper`` package has several responsibilities:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1151
msgid ""
"It sets the ``CC``, ``CXX``, and ``FC`` environment variables in the :ref:"
"`build environment <environment-variables>`. These variables point to a "
"wrapper executable in the ``compiler-wrapper``'s bin directory, which is a "
"shell script that ultimately invokes the actual, underlying compiler "
"executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1153
msgid ""
"It ensures that three kinds of compiler flags are passed to the compiler "
"when it is invoked:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1155
msgid ""
"Flags requested by the user and package author (see :ref:`compiler flags "
"<compiler_flags>`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1156
msgid ""
"Flags needed to locate headers and libraries (during the build as well as at "
"runtime)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1157
msgid ""
"Target specific flags, like ``-march=x86-64-v3``, translated from the spec's "
"``target=<target>`` variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1160
msgid "Automatic search flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1162
msgid "The flags to locate headers and libraries are the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1164
msgid ""
"Compile-time library search paths: ``-L$dep_prefix/lib``, ``-L$dep_prefix/"
"lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1165
msgid ""
"Runtime library search paths (RPATHs): ``-Wl,-rpath,$dep_prefix/lib``, ``-"
"Wl,-rpath,$dep_prefix/lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1166
msgid "Include search paths: ``-I$dep_prefix/include``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1168
msgid ""
"These flags are added automatically for *each* link-type dependency (and "
"their transitive dependencies) of the package. The exact format of these "
"flags is determined by the compiler being used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1171
msgid ""
"These automatic flags are particularly useful in build systems such as "
"``AutotoolsPackage``, ``MakefilePackage`` and certain ``PythonPackage`` "
"packages that also contain C/C++ code. Typically configure scripts and "
"Makefiles just work out of the box: the right headers are included and the "
"right libraries are linked to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1174
msgid ""
"For example, consider a ``libdwarf`` package that just depends on ``libelf`` "
"and specifies it is written in C:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1176
msgid ""
"from spack.package import *\n"
"from spack_repo.builtin.build_systems.autotools import AutotoolsPackage\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Libdwarf(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    url = \"...\"\n"
"    version(\"1.0\", sha256=\"...\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"c\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"libelf\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1188
msgid ""
"You may not even have to implement :ref:`helper methods <spec-objects>` like "
"``configure_args`` to make it work. In the ``configure`` stage Spack by "
"default simply :ref:`runs <running_build_executables>` ``configure(f\"--"
"prefix={prefix}\")``. The configure script picks up the compiler wrapper "
"from the ``CC`` environment variable, and continues to run tests to find the "
"``libelf`` headers and libraries. Because the compiler wrapper is set up to "
"automatically include the ``-I<libelf prefix>/include`` and ``-L<libelf "
"prefix>/lib`` flags, the configure script succeeds and uses the correct "
"``libelf.h`` header and the ``libelf.so`` library out of the box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1196
msgid "Runtime library search paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1197
msgid ""
"Spack heavily makes use of `RPATHs <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rpath>`_ on "
"Linux and macOS to make executables directly runnable after installation. "
"Executables are able to find their needed libraries *without* any of the "
"infamous environment variables such as ``LD_LIBRARY_PATH`` on Linux or "
"``DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH`` on macOS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1200
msgid ""
"The :ref:`compiler wrapper <compiler-wrappers>` is the main component that "
"ensures that all binaries built by Spack have the correct RPATHs set. As a "
"package author, you rarely need to worry about RPATHs: the relevant compiler "
"flags are automatically injected through the compiler wrappers, and the "
"build system is blissfully unaware of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1203
msgid ""
"This works for most packages and build systems, with the notable exception "
"of CMake, which has its own RPATH handling. CMake has its own RPATH "
"handling, and distinguishes between build and install RPATHs. By default, "
"during the build it registers RPATHs to all libraries it links to, so that "
"just-built executables can be run during the build itself. Upon "
"installation, these RPATHs are cleared, unless the user defines the install "
"RPATHs. If you use the ``CMakePackage``, Spack automatically sets the "
"``CMAKE_INSTALL_RPATH_USE_LINK_PATH`` and ``CMAKE_INSTALL_RPATH`` defines to "
"ensure that the install RPATHs are set correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1209
msgid ""
"For packages that do not fit ``CMakePackage`` but still run ``cmake`` as "
"part of the build, it is recommended to look at :meth:`spack_repo.builtin."
"build_systems.cmake.CMakeBuilder.std_args` on how to set the install RPATHs "
"correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1213
msgid "MPI support in Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1217
msgid ""
"The MPI support section is somewhat outdated and will be updated in the "
"future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1232
msgid ""
"It is common for high-performance computing software/packages to use the "
"Message Passing Interface ( ``MPI``). As a result of concretization, a given "
"package can be built using different implementations of MPI such as "
"``OpenMPI``, ``MPICH`` or ``IntelMPI``. That is, when your package declares "
"that it ``depends_on(\"mpi\")``, it can be built with any of these ``mpi`` "
"implementations. In some scenarios, to configure a package, one has to "
"provide it with appropriate MPI compiler wrappers such as ``mpicc``, ``mpic+"
"+``. However, different implementations of ``MPI`` may have different names "
"for those wrappers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1238
msgid ""
"Spack provides an idiomatic way to use MPI compilers in your package. To use "
"MPI wrappers to compile your whole build, do this in your ``install()`` "
"method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1241
#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1282
msgid ""
"env[\"CC\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc\n"
"env[\"CXX\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpicxx\n"
"env[\"F77\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpif77\n"
"env[\"FC\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpifc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1248
msgid "That's all. A longer explanation of why this works is below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1251
msgid ""
"We don't try to force any particular build method on packagers. The decision "
"to use MPI wrappers depends on the way the package is written, on common "
"practice, and on \"what works\". Loosely, there are three types of MPI "
"builds:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1255
msgid ""
"Some build systems work well without the wrappers and can treat MPI as an "
"external library, where the person doing the build has to supply includes/"
"libs/etc. This is fairly uncommon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1258
msgid ""
"Others really want the wrappers and assume you're using an MPI \"compiler\" "
"-- i.e., they have no mechanism to add MPI includes/libraries/etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1260
msgid ""
"CMake's ``FindMPI`` needs the compiler wrappers, but it uses them to extract "
"``-I`` / ``-L`` / ``-D`` arguments, then treats MPI like a regular library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1262
msgid ""
"Note that some CMake builds fall into case 2 because they either don't know "
"about or don't like CMake's ``FindMPI`` support -- they just assume an MPI "
"compiler. Also, some Autotools builds fall into case 3 (e.g., `here is an "
"autotools version of CMake's FindMPI <https://github.com/tgamblin/libra/blob/"
"master/m4/lx_find_mpi.m4>`_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1265
msgid ""
"Given all of this, we leave the use of the wrappers up to the packager. "
"Spack will support all three ways of building MPI packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1269
msgid "Packaging Conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1271
msgid ""
"As mentioned above, in the ``install()`` method, ``CC``, ``CXX``, ``F77``, "
"and ``FC`` point to Spack's wrappers around the chosen compiler. Spack's "
"wrappers are not the MPI compiler wrappers, though they do automatically add "
"``-I``, ``-L``, and ``-Wl,-rpath`` args for dependencies in a similar way. "
"The MPI wrappers are a bit different in that they also add ``-l`` arguments "
"for the MPI libraries, and some add special ``-D`` arguments to trigger "
"build options in MPI programs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1275
msgid ""
"For case 1 above, you generally don't need to do more than patch your "
"Makefile or add configure args as you normally would."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1277
msgid ""
"For case 3, you don't need to do much of anything, as Spack puts the MPI "
"compiler wrappers in the PATH, and the build will find them and interrogate "
"them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1279
msgid ""
"For case 2, things are a bit more complicated, as you'll need to tell the "
"build to use the MPI compiler wrappers instead of Spack's compiler wrappers. "
"All it takes is some lines like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1289
msgid ""
"Or, if you pass CC, CXX, etc. directly to your build with, e.g., ``--with-"
"cc=<path>``, you'll want to substitute ``spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc`` in there "
"instead, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1291
msgid ""
"configure(\"--prefix=%s\" % prefix, \"--with-cc=%s\" % spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1295
msgid ""
"Now, you may think that doing this will lose the includes, library paths, "
"and RPATHs that Spack's compiler wrappers get you, but we've actually set "
"things up so that the MPI compiler wrappers use Spack's compiler wrappers "
"when run from within Spack. So using the MPI wrappers should really be as "
"simple as the code above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1299
msgid "``spec[\"mpi\"]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1301
msgid "Okay, so how does all this work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1303
msgid ""
"If your package has a virtual dependency like ``mpi``, then referring to "
"``spec[\"mpi\"]`` within ``install()`` will get you the concrete ``mpi`` "
"implementation in your dependency DAG. That is a spec object just like the "
"one passed to install, only the MPI implementations all set some additional "
"properties on it to help you out. E.g., in ``openmpi``, you'll find this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1307
msgid ""
"    def setup_dependent_package(self, module, dependent_spec):\n"
"        self.spec.mpicc = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpicc\")\n"
"        self.spec.mpicxx = join_path(self.prefix.bin, self.cxxname)\n"
"        # Some derived packages define the \"fortran\" variant, most don't. "
"Checking on the\n"
"        # presence of ~fortran makes us default to add fortran wrappers if "
"the variant is\n"
"        # not declared.\n"
"        if self.spec.satisfies(\"~fortran\"):\n"
"            return\n"
"        self.spec.mpifc = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpif90\")\n"
"        self.spec.mpif77 = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpif77\")\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1310
msgid ""
"That code allows the ``openmpi`` package to associate an ``mpicc`` property "
"with the ``openmpi`` spec in the DAG, so that dependents can access it. "
"``mvapich2`` and ``mpich`` do similar things. So, no matter what MPI you're "
"using, ``spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc`` gets you the location of the MPI compilers. "
"This allows us to have a fairly simple polymorphic interface for information "
"about virtual dependencies like MPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1316
msgid "Wrapping wrappers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1318
msgid ""
"Spack likes to use its own compiler wrappers to make it easy to add "
"``RPATHs`` to builds, and to try hard to ensure that your builds use the "
"right dependencies. This doesn't play nicely by default with MPI, so we have "
"to do a couple of tricks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1321
msgid ""
"If we build MPI with Spack's wrappers, ``mpicc`` and friends will be "
"installed with hard-coded paths to Spack's wrappers, and using them from "
"outside of Spack will fail because they only work within Spack. To fix this, "
"we patch ``mpicc`` and friends to use the regular compilers. Look at the "
"filter_compilers method in ``mpich``, ``openmpi``, or ``mvapich2`` for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1325
msgid ""
"We still want to use the Spack compiler wrappers when Spack is calling "
"``mpicc``. Luckily, wrappers in all mainstream MPI implementations provide "
"environment variables that allow us to dynamically set the compiler to be "
"used by ``mpicc``, ``mpicxx``, etc. Spack's build environment sets "
"``MPICC``, ``MPICXX``, etc. for MPICH derivatives and ``OMPI_CC``, "
"``OMPI_CXX``, etc. for OpenMPI. This makes the MPI compiler wrappers use the "
"Spack compiler wrappers so that your dependencies still get proper RPATHs "
"even if you use the MPI wrappers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1331
msgid "MPI on Cray machines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1333
msgid ""
"The Cray programming environment notably uses its own compiler wrappers, "
"which function like MPI wrappers. On Cray systems, the ``CC``, ``cc``, and "
"``ftn`` wrappers ARE the MPI compiler wrappers, and it's assumed that you'll "
"use them for all of your builds. So on Cray we don't bother with ``mpicc``, "
"``mpicxx``, etc., Spack MPI implementations set ``spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc`` to "
"point to Spack's wrappers, which wrap the Cray wrappers, which wrap the "
"regular compilers and include MPI flags. That may seem complicated, but for "
"packagers, that means the same code for using MPI wrappers will work, even "
"on a Cray:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1338
msgid "env[\"CC\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1342
msgid "This is because on Cray, ``spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc`` is just ``spack_cc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1347
msgid "Packaging workflow and commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1349
msgid ""
"When you are building packages, you will likely not get things completely "
"right the first time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1351
msgid ""
"After having :doc:`created a package <packaging_guide_creation>`, the edit-"
"install loop is a common workflow to get the package building correctly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1353
msgid ""
"$ spack edit mypackage\n"
"$ spack install --verbose mypackage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1358
msgid ""
"Whenever a build fails, Spack retains the build directory for you to "
"inspect. The location of the build directory is printed in the build output, "
"but you can also find it with the ``spack locate`` command, or navigate to "
"it directly using ``spack cd``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1361
msgid ""
"$ spack locate mypackage\n"
"/tmp/spack-stage/spack-stage-mypackage-1-2-3-abcdef\n"
"\n"
"$ spack cd mypackage\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/tmp/spack-stage/spack-stage-mypackage-1-2-3-abcdef"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1371
msgid "Inspecting the build environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1373
msgid ""
"Once you have navigated to the build directory after a failed build, you may "
"also want to manually run build commands to troubleshoot the issue. This "
"requires you to have all environment variables exactly set up as they are in "
"the :ref:`build environment <environment-variables>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1376
msgid "The command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1378
msgid "$ spack build-env mypackage -- /bin/sh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1382
msgid ""
"is a convenient way to start a subshell with the build environment variables "
"set up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1385
msgid "Keeping the stage directory on success"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1387
msgid ""
"Sometimes a build completes successfully, but you encounter issues only when "
"you try to run the installed package. In such cases, it can be useful to "
"keep the build directory area to find out what went wrong."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1390
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack install`` will delete the staging area once a package "
"has been successfully built and installed. Use ``--keep-stage`` to leave the "
"build directory intact:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1393
msgid "$ spack install --keep-stage <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1397
msgid ""
"This allows you to inspect the build directory and potentially debug the "
"build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1399
msgid "Once done, you could remove all sources and build directories with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1401
msgid "$ spack clean --stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1406
msgid "Keeping the install prefix on failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1408
msgid ""
"Conversely, if a build fails but *has* installed some files, you may want to "
"keep the install prefix to diagnose the issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1410
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack install`` deletes the install directory if anything "
"fails during build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1412
msgid ""
"The ``--keep-prefix`` option allows you to keep the install prefix "
"regardless of the build outcome."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1414
msgid "$ spack install --keep-prefix <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1421
msgid "Understanding the DAG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1423
msgid ""
"Sometimes when you are packaging software, it is useful to have a better "
"understanding of the dependency graph of a package. The ``spack spec "
"<spec>`` command gives you a good overview of dependencies right on the "
"command line, but the tree structure may not be entirely clear. The ``spack "
"graph <spec>`` command can help you visualize the dependency graph better."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1427
msgid ""
"By default it generates an ASCII rendering of a spec's dependency graph, "
"which can be complementary to the output of ``spack spec``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1429
msgid ""
"Much more powerful is the set of flags ``spack graph --color --dot ...``, "
"which turns the dependency graph into `Dot <http://www.graphviz.org/doc/info/"
"lang.html>`_ format. Tools such as `Graphviz <http://www.graphviz.org>`_ can "
"render this. For example, you can generate a PDF of the dependency graph of "
"a package with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1433
msgid "$ spack graph --dot hdf5 | dot -Tpdf > hdf5.pdf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1437
msgid ""
"There are several online tools that can render Dot files directly in your "
"browser as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1439
msgid ""
"Another useful flag is ``spack graph --deptype=...`` which can reduce the "
"size of the graph, by filtering out certain types of dependencies. For "
"example, supplying ``--deptype=link`` will limit to link type dependencies "
"only. The default is ``--deptype=all``, which is equivalent to ``--"
"deptype=build,link,run,test``. Options for ``deptype`` include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1444
msgid ""
"Any combination of ``build``, ``link``, ``run``, and ``test`` separated by "
"commas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_build.rst:1445
msgid "``all`` for all types of dependencies."
msgstr ""
